00:17:27.390 --> 00:17:30.930
So the idea of this
is your information

00:17:30.930 --> 00:17:34.310
design, your interaction
design, and your visual design,

00:17:34.310 --> 00:17:39.170
should kind of have a different
balance between your own brand

00:17:39.170 --> 00:17:44.630
and the Holo or Android visual
style and design language.

00:17:44.630 --> 00:17:47.670
So the information
design, the architecture

00:17:47.670 --> 00:17:53.000
of your app, how information
flows throughout your app,

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:58.190
and also how a user
understands the interactions,

00:17:58.190 --> 00:18:03.270
the mental model-- those
are very, very brandable.

00:18:03.270 --> 00:18:08.530
And you should express
your information design

00:18:08.530 --> 00:18:11.610
as creatively as
you can and really

00:18:11.610 --> 00:18:17.740
let your simplicity and
your branding shine there.

00:18:17.740 --> 00:18:19.470
On the other hand,
interaction design--

00:18:19.470 --> 00:18:24.090
you don't want to introduce
new interaction patterns

00:18:24.090 --> 00:18:29.160
for simple navigation or high
level switching between views.

00:18:29.160 --> 00:18:32.490
Because extra stuff that
the platform already

00:18:32.490 --> 00:18:34.020
does for you for
free is just going

00:18:34.020 --> 00:18:38.340
to confuse users or add steps
for them to learn how to use

00:18:38.340 --> 00:18:40.810
your app, when you
should really just

00:18:40.810 --> 00:18:44.760
be finding the right fit
for existing patterns

00:18:44.760 --> 00:18:48.700
and, where needed,
extending those.

00:18:48.700 --> 00:18:53.150
So it's not necessarily that all
the components that we provide

00:18:53.150 --> 00:18:56.200
in the platform are the only
things you should use, right?

00:18:56.200 --> 00:18:58.470
But if you need a little
extra flexibility,

00:18:58.470 --> 00:19:01.120
you should at least use
one of the base components

00:19:01.120 --> 00:19:03.840
as a starting point.

00:19:03.840 --> 00:19:06.060
And then for visual
design, which

00:19:06.060 --> 00:19:10.600
is what most people
associate with branding,

00:19:10.600 --> 00:19:12.210
you want to strike a balance.

00:19:12.210 --> 00:19:15.460
So they pointed
out in the episode

00:19:15.460 --> 00:19:20.730
that the best way, probably,
to use your branding,

00:19:20.730 --> 00:19:23.040
to highlight your branding
in your visual design is

00:19:23.040 --> 00:19:25.690
through the use of
a branded color.

00:19:28.610 --> 00:19:31.500
A fantastic example of this
is throughout the Play apps

00:19:31.500 --> 00:19:35.260
where each Play property
has its own color.

00:19:35.260 --> 00:19:37.460
And that helps
between multiple apps

00:19:37.460 --> 00:19:40.920
to keep you kind of in context
of which property you're

00:19:40.920 --> 00:19:42.640
dealing with at the time.

00:19:42.640 --> 00:19:45.520
Now for most people
out there, they're

00:19:45.520 --> 00:19:47.940
not going to be developing a
suite of apps like the Play

00:19:47.940 --> 00:19:49.220
Store.

00:19:49.220 --> 00:19:52.570
But at the same time, you
don't want your user interface

00:19:52.570 --> 00:19:54.670
to be your brand.

00:19:54.670 --> 00:19:56.470
The navigation is not the brand.

00:19:56.470 --> 00:20:01.690
The way this button looks
can kind of be your brand.

00:20:01.690 --> 00:20:05.260
So that's where this slider is
kind of halfway in the middle.

00:20:05.260 --> 00:20:09.550
You want to take the core look
and feel of the Holo design

00:20:09.550 --> 00:20:12.740
language and then extend that.

00:20:12.740 --> 00:20:16.060
Don't, you know, replace
the right angle triangle

00:20:16.060 --> 00:20:19.290
in the spinner drop down
with something else.

00:20:19.290 --> 00:20:21.560
You know, start with
that familiar place,

00:20:21.560 --> 00:20:25.560
and then you can kind of
use those expected metaphors

00:20:25.560 --> 00:20:28.250
and visual indicators
throughout,

00:20:28.250 --> 00:20:32.690
so that users know exactly how
a component-- even if it isn't

00:20:32.690 --> 00:20:34.150
exactly as it
looks, they'll know

00:20:34.150 --> 00:20:36.010
how it can be used
because you're

00:20:36.010 --> 00:20:38.510
kind of starting
at the right place.

00:20:38.510 --> 00:20:40.260
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah,
that's a great summary.

00:20:40.260 --> 00:20:43.650
Basically if you're
going to make something,

00:20:43.650 --> 00:20:45.870
you should make your U/I
elements interesting.

00:20:45.870 --> 00:20:48.680
You give them some
extra, you know,

00:20:48.680 --> 00:20:52.630
bit of-- put in that
extra punch of branding.

00:20:52.630 --> 00:20:54.710
But make sure they're
still very, very familiar

00:20:54.710 --> 00:20:57.550
because you really want to
lean on what you already know.

00:20:57.550 --> 00:20:59.300
And what users already
know are the things

00:20:59.300 --> 00:21:04.900
that are in apps like Gmail,
and Google Keep, and Chrome.

00:21:04.900 --> 00:21:07.480
Things like the overflow,
things like tabs

00:21:07.480 --> 00:21:09.160
and the navigation
drawer, those things

00:21:09.160 --> 00:21:11.005
exist in terms of
interaction design.

00:21:11.005 --> 00:21:12.380
For visual design
you really want

00:21:12.380 --> 00:21:14.360
to take that and
kind of extend Holo.

00:21:14.360 --> 00:21:17.850
Not replace it, not
use it wholesale.

00:21:17.850 --> 00:21:20.010
But really extend it, and
really kind of pump it

00:21:20.010 --> 00:21:23.264
with your own sense, with
your own branding I guess.

00:21:23.264 --> 00:21:24.430
MIKE DENNY: Yeah definitely.

00:21:24.430 --> 00:21:27.160
And the design principle
from the Android Design Guide

00:21:27.160 --> 00:21:31.190
that really is expressed here
is that users should have tricks

00:21:31.190 --> 00:21:32.970
that they can use everywhere.

00:21:32.970 --> 00:21:35.920
And so that's what we've
been talking about.

00:21:35.920 --> 00:21:37.910
These little visual
indicators that users

00:21:37.910 --> 00:21:41.110
expect to behave in a certain
way, don't go replacing that

00:21:41.110 --> 00:21:44.510
just because you
think it looks cool.

