00:23:00.980 --> 00:23:04.570
Additional things that
can be pretty annoying

00:23:04.570 --> 00:23:08.530
are showing modal
loading dialogs.

00:23:08.530 --> 00:23:10.730
The best way to
deal with loading

00:23:10.730 --> 00:23:12.850
in data asynchronously
over the network

00:23:12.850 --> 00:23:16.460
is to do it before you
show it to the user.

00:23:16.460 --> 00:23:19.030
So wherever possible,
obviously that's

00:23:19.030 --> 00:23:20.770
not possible in every
case, especially

00:23:20.770 --> 00:23:23.250
for real-time
updates-- if the user

00:23:23.250 --> 00:23:26.540
wants to update a social
feed, for example.

00:23:26.540 --> 00:23:30.350
But when presenting
a loading indicator,

00:23:30.350 --> 00:23:32.780
it's best to do it in
line, either with the U/I

00:23:32.780 --> 00:23:36.940
element that's currently loading
or somewhere more prominent

00:23:36.940 --> 00:23:40.080
on the action bar, for example,
to indicate that something's

00:23:40.080 --> 00:23:43.880
loading in from the network,
but not necessarily a popup

00:23:43.880 --> 00:23:46.730
dialog that blocks
off your action.

00:23:46.730 --> 00:23:50.830
The worst thing about this
is when you override the Back

00:23:50.830 --> 00:23:54.630
button so that you can't cancel
the dialog until the loading

00:23:54.630 --> 00:23:56.420
process actually completes.

00:23:56.420 --> 00:23:57.970
So that's a big no-no.

00:23:57.970 --> 00:24:01.070
