for configuration of a widget.

00:36:03.980 --> 00:36:05.960
So one of the great
things about widgets

00:36:05.960 --> 00:36:08.480
is that they let a user
take a bit of your app

00:36:08.480 --> 00:36:11.160
and put it on their home screen,
one of the most valuable pieces

00:36:11.160 --> 00:36:12.924
of real estate on their device.

00:36:12.924 --> 00:36:15.090
And one of the best ways
to have a successful widget

00:36:15.090 --> 00:36:18.260
is to allow customization,
really let the user make it

00:36:18.260 --> 00:36:19.880
their own.

00:36:19.880 --> 00:36:22.740
We also talked about some
best practices for sizing.

00:36:22.740 --> 00:36:25.550
Basically when you're designing
the layout for a widget,

00:36:25.550 --> 00:36:27.020
we talked about
some formulas you

00:36:27.020 --> 00:36:29.545
can use to roughly figure
out how big it should be.

00:36:29.545 --> 00:36:31.920
NICK BUTCHER: I think one of
the most important things we

00:36:31.920 --> 00:36:34.560
touched on there which perhaps
isn't quite as well-documented

00:36:34.560 --> 00:36:37.220
as I'd like in our
design guidelines,

00:36:37.220 --> 00:36:39.600
is the fact that you're
sharing some real estate.

00:36:39.600 --> 00:36:42.930
So while your app has the
full range of expression

00:36:42.930 --> 00:36:45.670
of its brand, and
so forth, when it's

00:36:45.670 --> 00:36:48.400
taking over the whole screen,
when you are creating a widget,

00:36:48.400 --> 00:36:50.602
you have to bear in
mind the context that it

00:36:50.602 --> 00:36:53.060
will be presented next to other
widgets or other app icons.

00:36:53.060 --> 00:36:54.976
So I think that was a
really important section

00:36:54.976 --> 00:36:55.890
in that episode.

